<br>
Roleplay names:<br>
<br>
Things like Lorec <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> , Bjond, Kamaya.  Names that are meant to help the reader immerse themselves in the world, that have no relationship (or the relationship is sufficiently obscure) to the real world.<br>
<br>
Lazy Roleplay names:<br>
<br>
Take-off's on characters from popular (or unpopular) fiction and movies.  There is a whole  slew (maybe two) of these running around Gfay after Lord of the Ring, halflings named Bhilbo, people with names like Boorumer, Ghandulf, shadowknights named Sauhron.... Etc.  These are often younger players, so I find this not too offensive, but I also find that these are much less likely to play in character.  Just my experience.<br>
<br>
Clever names:<br>
<br>
Things like Itchibum for an Ogre (back when Ogres still scratched there bottoms), Brik (another Ogre I knew), Grauk Dat (an SK twink I once had).  I think it is much more appropriate for &quot;simple&quot; races like ogre's to name themselves after what they do ( eg butt scratching) than say an Erudite (at least for first name), but to each their own. <br>
<br>
Flippant names:<br>
<br>
These are often on characters who are designed for a purpose.  Never will advance terribly far.  Names like Joebobsmule, Taxxi, etc. Casual names are created out of laziness, or because the character is just an alt with a purpose.<br>
<br>
Obnoxious names: <br>
<br>
These can get pretty bad, on luclin a player was banned for a name something like Kiltha Blakks.  Bordering on this category<br>
are the myriad Wood Elf females named Kewty, or similar names.  Sure, that can be a roleplay nickname.  Your dad, the king of the elves, may have kissed you on your pointed little ears and called you that when you were tucked in at night, your friends might call you that, but its not on your Druid Guild ID card...<br>
<br>
One problem with the naming policy is that its arbritrated by people.  They have a lousy filter that catches just about every roleplay name I try and create, but lets the Chainman's, Taxxi's, joebobsmule's and Kewty Py's pass through.   The policy is obscurely located.  People don't always know that they aren't supposed to use names from other fictional sources, that they aren't supposed to use real words, or subtly alter them.  Anciient.  I am suprised they did'nt nerf your first name as well as your last, it violates the letter of their policy in the same way your surname did.  Though they really hesitate to do that as it is a way for people to escape a bad reputation (Not at all saying this is true in your case).<br>
<br>
Note:  none of this was meant to be offending, though of course some of it probably was, and I think the real fault iswith Verant for letting innapropriate names through the filters in the first place.  If they didn't like the surname Guardiian why didn't it get rejected at lvl 20 when Anciient typed /surname Guardiian....<br>
